19:T92e,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What does the AI Readiness Assessment actually measure?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The assessment evaluates your business across five dimensions: your current workflow type, the complexity of decisions in that workflow, the availability and quality of your data, the frequency and volume of the workflow, and your team size. Scores combine into an overall AI Readiness level — from Foundation First (5–7) through Getting Ready (8–10), Good Candidate (11–12), and Ready to Navigate (13–15)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What if I score low on readiness?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"A low readiness score does not mean you cannot start. It means you start differently. Every readiness band has a recommended next action. A business in the Foundation First band typically needs to focus on process standardisation and data capture before deploying AI."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I be ready for AI in one area of my business but not another?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, and this is actually the most common situation. A company might be ready to deploy AI in customer communication while its inventory management workflow needs foundational work first. The AI Navigator framework helps you identify and sequence these opportunities correctly."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does AI readiness require a large technology budget?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Some of the highest-ROI AI implementations for SMEs involve using existing large language models configured with your specific business context rather than building custom models from scratch. The AI Navigator framework specifically distinguishes between use cases that require significant investment and those that can be deployed quickly and cost-effectively."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How quickly can a business go from not ready to ready?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"For Tier 1 quick wins — use cases that do not require historical training data — a business can go from assessment to deployed AI in 30 to 60 days. For data-dependent Tier 2 use cases, data collection adds 30 to 60 days. For Tier 3 implementations, 6 to 12 months of live operational data is typically required."}}]}f:[["$","$L2",null,{"id":"faq-schema","type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"$19"}}],null,["$","div",null,{"className":"article-wrap","children":[["$","nav",null,{"className":"breadcrumb","aria-label":"Breadcrumb","children":[["$","a",null,{"href":"/","children":"Home"}],["$","span",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","children":" › "}],["$","a",null,{"href":"/resources/","children":"Resources"}],["$","span",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","children":" › "}],["$","span",null,{"children":"Is Your Business Ready for AI? 5 Questions to Find Out"}]]}],["$","h1",null,{"children":"Is Your Business Ready for AI? 5 Questions to Find Out"}],[["$","p","0",{"children":"Most business owners in Qatar asking this question already know they want to use AI. What they do not know is whether they are starting from the right position — whether their workflows, data, team, and processes are actually set up to make AI work rather than just run."}],["$","p","1",{"children":"These five questions are drawn directly from Chapter 2 of the AI Navigator framework — the Starting Point Analysis. They are the same questions used in every AI Navigator engagement to establish the honest baseline before any planning begins."}]],"$L1a",["$L1b","$L1c","$L1d","$L1e","$L1f","$L20"],"$L21","$L22","$undefined","$L23","$L24"]}]]
